---
title: 'The Harada Method: One Goal, Eight Spokes, A Whole Life'
pillars: [learns, lives]
publishedDate: 2026-07-20
excerpt: >-
  A planning method used by one of the best athletes in the world led me to a
  question I'd been avoiding since my health scare this year: what do I actually
  want, and am I willing to put myself at the center of my own plan?
---
I came across the Harada method through a video about Shohei Ohtani, who used it to structure his path to becoming one of the best baseball players in the world. A planning method built to manifest a dream life caught my attention immediately — I'm already the kind of person who loves a plan, who needs to see the steps laid out before I can move through them one at a time.

So I went looking for more. I asked Claude directly what the Harada method was and how I might apply it to my own life.

## A reason to look closer

Earlier this year, a health scare kept me mostly homebound for a few months. It reframed things. Looking at my life as it stood, I knew plainly that it wasn't what I wanted — and that getting somewhere different would take more than a vague wish. It would take something specific enough to act on.

The Harada method fit that need. It's an established framework, not something improvised, and it forces a big, vague feeling down into concrete, workable pieces.

---

## Choosing your eight spokes

The method centers on eight "spokes" — the supporting areas of a full life, each radiating out from one main goal. I sat down and started naming mine. Career. Spirituality. Exercise and living well. Travel. A few others followed.

[[note: The eight spokes aren't fixed — you choose what belongs in your own wheel. That choice is most of the exercise.]]

What surprised me wasn't the list itself, but what the act of choosing did to my thinking. Writing down what mattered to me, in my own words, made things clearer than they'd been in months.

---

## Naming the thing at the center

The harder part was the center: the one goal everything else is meant to support. "A new life" is not an answer — it's a feeling wearing the shape of one. Naming it required sitting with the question long enough to find language specific enough to act on.

I landed on something. What it was isn't the point of this post. The exercise is.

==Vague wanting doesn't move you anywhere. Naming does.==

Because here is what I kept returning to: so much of our lives, especially as women, are built around other people. Our needs get pushed to the back burner quietly, without anyone deciding it on purpose. What waits at the end of that is frustration, disappointment, a low hum of unfulfillment — none of it good.

If there's one thing worth taking from this, it's to put yourself first. Not just in feeling, but in practice: give yourself an actual, structured way to work toward the life you want, rather than only dreaming about it from the sidelines.

---

## Field notes: how to build your own Harada wheel this week

**1. Start with a real conversation, not a search bar.** Ask an AI tool directly — "What is the Harada method, and how do I apply it to my own life?" — and let it walk you through the framework before committing to anything.

**2. Name your main goal.** The one everything else should feed into. Be as specific as you can.

**3. Map eight areas of support.** Health, skills, mindset, relationships — whatever your version of these spokes looks like. Each one is a spoke on your wheel.

**4. Identify what's weak.** A wheel with one broken spoke wobbles. That area needs attention first.

**5. Build daily routines per spoke.** Systems beat motivation — small, repeatable actions that compound toward the goal.

If you want the method in its original, fuller form, **The Harada Method: The Spirit of Self-Reliance** by Takashi Harada and Norman Bodek lays out the whole framework, spokes and all: [The Harada Method on Amazon](https://amzn.to/4vJG9XL)

---

## The reminder

You don't need permission to want something specific for your own life, and you don't need everyone else's needs settled first.

Sit down. Name your eight spokes. Name the thing at the center. Then start building the daily habits that point toward it.

If you've never heard of the Harada method before today, look into it. Consider your nucleus. Consider your eight spokes. You might be surprised by what you find.

